        </div>
        <p>
            Astrid Anna Emilia Lindgren, born Ericsson on November 14, 1907 in Vimmerby county parish in Småland, died January 28, 
            2002 in Stockholm, was a Swedish children's book, song lyrics and screenplay author as well as publishing editor and opinion leader. 
            Lindgren is known worldwide for his children's books about, among others, Pippi Longstocking (1945), Barnen i Bullerbyn (1947), 
            Karlsson på taket (1955), Madicken (1960), 
            Emil in Lönneberga (1963), The Salt Crow (1964), 
            The Brothers Lionheart (1973) and Ronja Rövardotter (1981). She considered that it was absurd that self-employed people could have to pay more in marginal tax than they earned. 
            The short story received a lot of attention and spread. The government's treatment of Lindgren, when Finance Minister 
            Gunnar Sträng first replied that Lindgren was profoundly ignorant of the errors of tax policy,[3] and later admitted 
            that she was right in substance, is considered to have been a contributing factor to the Social Democrats losing government 
            power for the first time in 40 year. 
        </p>
