         <p>
            She was also awarded an honorary doctorate at Linköping University, the University of Leicester 
            and the University of Warsaw. Several prizes have also been instituted in her name, the most important of which is 
            the Literature Prize in Astrid Lindgren's memory instituted in 2002 by the Swedish government. The prize sum is five
            million kroner[2], which makes it the world's largest literary prize after the Nobel Prize in Literature. During the
            latter part of his life, Lindgren was also a significant social debater.
            In the 1976 election campaign, her short story Pomperipossa i Monismanien was published in Expressen. 
